{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YQi6etajcd8tiat6PJWjm9","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# 02 — Materials & Physical Properties\n2\t\n3\tDesign/description material properties stated in ANL-ART-47. Each item cites its source section/\n4\ttable. These are stated design/material properties (allowed inputs), not measured test outcomes.\n5\t\n6\t---\n7\t\n8\t## 1. Structural / component materials (§3.1–§3.3)\n9\t| Component | Material |\n10\t|---|---|\n11\t| Base support | W12×65 I-beam sections |\n12\t| U-channel framework | ASTM A36 channels (MC12×45, MC6×18) on 1″ steel plates |\n13\t| Inlet plenum | Aluminum alloy 3003, 1/8″ thick |\n14\t| Riser ducts | ASTM A500 Grade B rectangular steel tubing, 10″×2″×0.188″ |\n15\t| Riser support plate | 1″ ASTM A36 steel |\n16\t| Outlet-plenum / west-wall panels | L3×2×1/4″ steel angle frame, 1/8″ aluminum skins |\n17\t| N/S unheated panels | 16-gauge aluminum alloy #3000 skin |\n18\t| Primary heated plate | SAE 1020 low-carbon steel, 1″ thick |\n19\t| Heater sub-panel sheets | Stainless steel (sandblasted, heat-treated 1900 °F) |\n20\t| Chimney ducts | 24″ dia, 14-gauge galvanized steel, 0.016″ Al jacket |\n21\t\n22\t### Primary heated-plate composition (§3.3.3)\n23\tSAE 1020 ladle composition limits: **0.18–0.23 % C, 0.30–0.60 % Mn, 0.040 % P (max), 0.50 % S (max),\n24\tbalance Fe.** Surface: mill-scale oxidized (thin, electrically non-conducting oxide, dull dark-purple\n25\tcoloration). (Plates were salvaged from the earlier PRISM/RVACS program.)\n26\t\n27\t---\n28\t\n29\t## 2. Surface emissivities (§3.3.3, §3.3.4, §4.2.2, §6.4.3)\n30\t| Surface | Emissivity | Source |\n31\t|---|---|---|\n32\t| Primary heated plate (mill-scale oxidized) | initially 0.7–0.9; **measured pre-test avg 0.78–0.79** | §3.3.3 |\n33\t| Heater sub-panel stainless sheets (post sandblast/heat-treat) | ≈ 0.90 (from ≈ 0.25 before) | §3.3.4 |\n34\t| Heat-flux-sensor matte-black surface | ε ≈ 1.0 | §4.2.2 |\n35\t| Heat-flux-sensor reflective (golden polyimide) surface | ε ≪ 1.0 | §4.2.2 |\n36\t| NSTF cavity sidewalls (assumed in view-factor analysis) | 0.2 | §6.4.3 |\n37\t\n38\tNote: the plate emissivity 0.78–0.79 is a pre-test surface-property calibration of the plate material\n39\t(a modeling input for radiation), not a test-performance result.\n40\t\n41\t---\n42\t\n43\t## 3. Insulation materials & thermal specifications (§3.4, Table 9)\n44\t\n45\tApplied locations: SuperIsol on all test-section insulated panels/walls; Duraboard LD as backing for\n46\tthe ceramic heaters; Enerywrap 80 on chimney ductwork; Durablanket S as filler/patchwork.\n47\t**Non-insulated** areas: inlet downcomer, inlet plenum, horizontal chimney (fan-loft) ducts.\n48\tNorth/south/west cavity walls include 6″ of Duraboard LD. Chimney: 3″ mineral wool + 0.016″ Al jacket.\n49\t\n50\tThermal conductivity values in **BTU·in/(hr·ft²·°F)** at the listed temperatures:\n51\t\n52\t| Material | Thickness | Max temp | Density | k values (°F: value) |\n53\t|---|---|---|---|---|\n54\t| Super Isol | 3″ | 1,800 °F | 16 pcf | 400 °F: 0.416 · 750 °F: 0.554 · 1100 °F: 0.693 |\n55\t| Duraboard LD | 2″ | 2,300 °F | 16 pcf | 400 °F: 0.55 · 1000 °F: 0.847 · 1600 °F: 1.339 |\n56\t| Durablanket S | 1″ | 2,150 °F | 8 pcf | 600 °F: 0.56 · 1000 °F: 0.977 · 1600 °F: 2.003 |\n57\t| Enerywrap 80 | 3″ | 1,200 °F | 8 pcf | 200 °F: 0.30 · 400 °F: 0.42 · 600 °F: 0.59 |\n58\t\n59\t(pcf = lb/ft³. To convert k: 1 BTU·in/(hr·ft²·°F) ≈ 0.1442 W/(m·K).)\n60\t\n61\t---\n62\t\n63\t## 4. Working-fluid physical properties (reference data, §7.4.2, Tables 46 & 47)\n64\t\n65\tThese are **standard published fluid properties** of dry air and argon (needed as modeling inputs for\n66\tthe natural-circulation working fluid and for the heavy-gas ingress scenario). They are reference\n67\tproperty values, not facility measurements.\n68\t\n69\t### Table 46 — Dry air & argon at STP (0 °C, 101.325 kPa)\n70\t| Property | Unit | Air (dry) | Argon |\n71\t|---|---|---|---|\n72\t| Molecular weight | g/mol | 28.970 | 39.948 |\n73\t| Density ρ | kg/m³ | 1.292 | 1.784 |\n74\t| Heat capacity Cp | kJ/kg·K | 1.005 | 0.522 |\n75\t| Thermal conductivity k | W/m·K | 0.024 | 0.016 |\n76\t| Prandtl Pr | – | 0.711 | 0.665 |\n77\t| Dynamic viscosity µ | ×10⁻⁶ N·s/m² | 17.220 | 21.020 |\n78\t\n79\t### Table 47 — Air & argon, 0 °C vs 100 °C (101.325 kPa)\n80\t| Property | Unit | Air 0 °C | Air 100 °C | Argon 0 °C | Argon 100 °C |\n81\t|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n82\t| Molecular weight | g/mol | 28.970 | 28.970 | 39.948 | 39.948 |\n83\t| Density ρ | kg/m³ | 1.292 | 0.946 | 1.784 | 1.305 |\n84\t| Heat capacity Cp | kJ/kg·K | 1.005 | 1.012 | 0.522 | 0.521 |\n85\t| Thermal conductivity k | W/m·K | 0.024 | 0.032 | 0.016 | 0.021 |\n86\t| Prandtl Pr | – | 0.711 | 0.701 | 0.665 | 0.664 |\n87\t| Dynamic viscosity µ | ×10⁻⁶ N·s/m² | 17.220 | 21.900 | 21.020 | 27.170 |\n88\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d866f6b4-d360-4fea-b150-307ad8af7258","uuid":"5a95dec2-8572-447f-95da-b50bfbb051bc","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:47:30.972Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/curated_v2/inputs/02_materials.md","content":"# 02 — Materials & Physical Properties\n\nDesign/description material properties stated in ANL-ART-47. Each item cites its source section/\ntable. These are stated design/material properties (allowed inputs), not measured test outcomes.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structural / component materials (§3.1–§3.3)\n| Component | Material |\n|---|---|\n| Base support | W12×65 I-beam sections |\n| U-channel framework | ASTM A36 channels (MC12×45, MC6×18) on 1″ steel plates |\n| Inlet plenum | Aluminum alloy 3003, 1/8″ thick |\n| Riser ducts | ASTM A500 Grade B rectangular steel tubing, 10″×2″×0.188″ |\n| Riser support plate | 1″ ASTM A36 steel |\n| Outlet-plenum / west-wall panels | L3×2×1/4″ steel angle frame, 1/8″ aluminum skins |\n| N/S unheated panels | 16-gauge aluminum alloy #3000 skin |\n| Primary heated plate | SAE 1020 low-carbon steel, 1″ thick |\n| Heater sub-panel sheets | Stainless steel (sandblasted, heat-treated 1900 °F) |\n| Chimney ducts | 24″ dia, 14-gauge galvanized steel, 0.016″ Al jacket |\n\n### Primary heated-plate composition (§3.3.3)\nSAE 1020 ladle composition limits: **0.18–0.23 % C, 0.30–0.60 % Mn, 0.040 % P (max), 0.50 % S (max),\nbalance Fe.** Surface: mill-scale oxidized (thin, electrically non-conducting oxide, dull dark-purple\ncoloration). (Plates were salvaged from the earlier PRISM/RVACS program.)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Surface emissivities (§3.3.3, §3.3.4, §4.2.2, §6.4.3)\n| Surface | Emissivity | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary heated plate (mill-scale oxidized) | initially 0.7–0.9; **measured pre-test avg 0.78–0.79** | §3.3.3 |\n| Heater sub-panel stainless sheets (post sandblast/heat-treat) | ≈ 0.90 (from ≈ 0.25 before) | §3.3.4 |\n| Heat-flux-sensor matte-black surface | ε ≈ 1.0 | §4.2.2 |\n| Heat-flux-sensor reflective (golden polyimide) surface | ε ≪ 1.0 | §4.2.2 |\n| NSTF cavity sidewalls (assumed in view-factor analysis) | 0.2 | §6.4.3 |\n\nNote: the plate emissivity 0.78–0.79 is a pre-test surface-property calibration of the plate material\n(a modeling input for radiation), not a test-performance result.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Insulation materials & thermal specifications (§3.4, Table 9)\n\nApplied locations: SuperIsol on all test-section insulated panels/walls; Duraboard LD as backing for\nthe ceramic heaters; Enerywrap 80 on chimney ductwork; Durablanket S as filler/patchwork.\n**Non-insulated** areas: inlet downcomer, inlet plenum, horizontal chimney (fan-loft) ducts.\nNorth/south/west cavity walls include 6″ of Duraboard LD. Chimney: 3″ mineral wool + 0.016″ Al jacket.\n\nThermal conductivity values in **BTU·in/(hr·ft²·°F)** at the listed temperatures:\n\n| Material | Thickness | Max temp | Density | k values (°F: value) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Super Isol | 3″ | 1,800 °F | 16 pcf | 400 °F: 0.416 · 750 °F: 0.554 · 1100 °F: 0.693 |\n| Duraboard LD | 2″ | 2,300 °F | 16 pcf | 400 °F: 0.55 · 1000 °F: 0.847 · 1600 °F: 1.339 |\n| Durablanket S | 1″ | 2,150 °F | 8 pcf | 600 °F: 0.56 · 1000 °F: 0.977 · 1600 °F: 2.003 |\n| Enerywrap 80 | 3″ | 1,200 °F | 8 pcf | 200 °F: 0.30 · 400 °F: 0.42 · 600 °F: 0.59 |\n\n(pcf = lb/ft³. To convert k: 1 BTU·in/(hr·ft²·°F) ≈ 0.1442 W/(m·K).)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Working-fluid physical properties (reference data, §7.4.2, Tables 46 & 47)\n\nThese are **standard published fluid properties** of dry air and argon (needed as modeling inputs for\nthe natural-circulation working fluid and for the heavy-gas ingress scenario). They are reference\nproperty values, not facility measurements.\n\n### Table 46 — Dry air & argon at STP (0 °C, 101.325 kPa)\n| Property | Unit | Air (dry) | Argon |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Molecular weight | g/mol | 28.970 | 39.948 |\n| Density ρ | kg/m³ | 1.292 | 1.784 |\n| Heat capacity Cp | kJ/kg·K | 1.005 | 0.522 |\n| Thermal conductivity k | W/m·K | 0.024 | 0.016 |\n| Prandtl Pr | – | 0.711 | 0.665 |\n| Dynamic viscosity µ | ×10⁻⁶ N·s/m² | 17.220 | 21.020 |\n\n### Table 47 — Air & argon, 0 °C vs 100 °C (101.325 kPa)\n| Property | Unit | Air 0 °C | Air 100 °C | Argon 0 °C | Argon 100 °C |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Molecular weight | g/mol | 28.970 | 28.970 | 39.948 | 39.948 |\n| Density ρ | kg/m³ | 1.292 | 0.946 | 1.784 | 1.305 |\n| Heat capacity Cp | kJ/kg·K | 1.005 | 1.012 | 0.522 | 0.521 |\n| Thermal conductivity k | W/m·K | 0.024 | 0.032 | 0.016 | 0.021 |\n| Prandtl Pr | – | 0.711 | 0.701 | 0.665 | 0.664 |\n| Dynamic viscosity µ | ×10⁻⁶ N·s/m² | 17.220 | 21.900 | 21.020 | 27.170 |\n","numLines":88,"startLine":1,"totalLines":88}}}
