{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RCgENaJhwJZGF8rJDzZLnn","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# 04 — Heater System & Test-Case Definitions (Controlled Inputs)\n2\t\n3\tControlled/boundary inputs from ANL-ART-47: heater power system (§4.3), baseline test definition\n4\t(§7.1), the accident decay-heat scenario (§6.4.1), power-shaping profiles (§6.4.2–§6.4.3), off-normal\n5\ttest-case definitions (§7.3–§7.4), and the ambient envelope (§1.5). Only *prescribed/controlled*\n6\tquantities are given; no measured system responses (flows, gas/wall/plate temperatures, removed\n7\tpower, ΔP, efficiency, fluxes) are included.\n8\t\n9\t---\n10\t\n11\t## 1. Heater power system & control (§3.3.5, §4.3)\n12\t- Source: **200 ceramic radiant heaters** (6″×12″×0.5″), 1,100 W each, **max 220 kWe**. Powered by\n13\t  480 & 240 VAC; 120 VAC per element.\n14\t- **40 control zones** = 20 \"main\" (8 heaters each) + 20 \"guard\" (2 heaters each). Nominal split:\n15\t  **80% of power from main zones, 20% from guard zones** (guards trim temperature uniformity).\n16\t- Spatial control grid: overall height split into **ten 67-cm axial segments**; at each axial\n17\t  elevation there are **4 azimuthal zones** (2 central + 2 guard) → 40 zones total.\n18\t- Operating modes: (i) constant heat flux (**max 21.6 kW/m²**), (ii) constant temperature\n19\t  (**max 677 °C**), or (iii) an arbitrary combination.\n20\t- Controllers: 40× **Eurotherm EPower** (600 VAC, 50 A), ±1% of full-scale power regulation;\n21\t  arranged in 5 banks × 4 substations; each zone hard-wired to a Mini8 controller with a safety\n22\t  trip set-point. Power-control mode moved from Phase-Angle to **Burst Firing** in later testing.\n23\t\n24\t---\n25\t\n26\t## 2. Baseline test case — the primary controlled reference (§3.5, §7.1)\n27\t\n28\tThe baseline simulates the GA-MHTGR depressurized-conduction-cooldown (DCC) **peak** decay-heat load\n29\tof 1.5 MWt full scale → **56 kWt** in the NSTF. Config (`baseline` operating state):\n30\t\n31\t1. **Heated–riser spacing:** 70.66 cm (27.82″).\n32\t2. **Outlet-plenum floor height:** 40.64 cm.\n33\t3. **Heater profile & power:** variable-burst, **linear across the 40 zones**; setpoints **56 kWe**\n34\t   and **82 kWe** (a 1st ramp to 56 kWe, then a 2nd ramp so that, after heat losses, ≈ 56 kWt reaches\n35\t   the heated section).\n36\t4. **Chimney:** open vertical stacks; cross-connect (XC) and fan lofts closed.\n37\t5. **Flow mode:** natural circulation; **dual vertical chimney** configuration.\n38\t\n39\tRun011 (the reference baseline run) prescribed two steady-state hold periods: **56 kWe** held ~6 h,\n40\tthen **82 kWe** held ~16 h. (Table 10 lists the nominal baseline heater power as 78 kWe; the\n41\texecutive summary and §7.1 describe the baseline near ~82 kWe.)\n42\t\n43\tBaseline \"as-set\" configuration values (from §3.5, Table 10): riser–heater spacing 0.71 m; riser flow\n44\tarea 0.155 m²; outlet-plenum floor spacing 0.41 m; outlet-plenum depth 1.88 m; chimney discharge\n45\theight 19.6 m; chimney flow area 0.58 m²; flow operation natural.\n46\t\n47\t---\n48\t\n49\t## 3. GA-MHTGR accident decay-heat scenario (§6.4.1, §7.3.1)\n50\t\n51\tScenario: begin at **normal** steady operation (700 kWt full → **26.16 kWt** NSTF), then follow a\n52\tprescribed decay-heat time history up to the DCC-with-small-primary-leak **peak** (1.5 MWt full →\n53\t**56.07 kWt** NSTF). Linear profile, natural circulation, dual vertical chimney.\n54\t\n55\t### Table 25 — Scaling ratios & resulting values (§6.4.1)\n56\t| Parameter | Scaling ratio | Full scale | ANL 1/2 scale |\n57\t|---|---|---|---|\n58\t| Power (normal) | Q̇R = √lR | 700 kWt | 26.16 kWt |\n59\t| Power (DCC accident) | Q̇R = √lR | 1,500 kWt | 56.07 kWt |\n60\t| Time | TR* = √lR | 120 hr | 84.85 hr |\n61\t\n62\t### Prescribed electrical-power decay curve (§6.4.1)\n63\tThe GA \"RCCS Removal\" decay curve was digitized, normalized to a peak of 1.5 MWt, and fit to a\n64\tpolynomial. The programmed NSTF electric power is:\n65\t\n66\t`P_watt,electric = [ C00 + C01·t + C02·t² + … + C09·t⁹ ] × Pscale`, with **t in minutes**,\n67\tand **Pscale = 90** (estimated to yield ≈ 56 kWt peak).\n68\t\n69\tFitted coefficients:\n70\t```\n71\tC00 =  466.531039994\n72\tC01 =  0.078631095079\n73\tC02 =  0.000170562320568\n74\tC03 = -1.28449427566e-007\n75\tC04 =  5.09424812301e-011\n76\tC05 = -1.27606140005e-014\n77\tC06 =  2.04789514471e-018\n78\tC07 = -2.08318254453e-022\n79\tC08 =  1.29530038954e-026\n80\tC09 = -4.48601180685e-031\n81\t```\n82\tCorrelation coefficient 0.999958043125; standard error about the line 1.46350115015.\n83\t(Report text describes a 10th-order fit; coefficients through C09 are those tabulated.)\n84\t\n85\tRun014/Run018 executed this scenario: initiate at normal steady load, then follow the scaled curve to\n86\tthe peak. (Run014 and Run018 are the winter and summer executions — see ambient conditions below.)\n87\t\n88\t---\n89\t\n90\t## 4. Power-shaping profiles (§6.4.2–§6.4.3)\n91\t\n92\t### 4.1 Cosine axial power profile (§6.4.2, Table 26)\n93\tAxial power skews were fit to the 40 zones with the integral power preserved. Peak positions\n94\t(normalized 0–1 axial): true cosine 0.5; MHTGR mid-plane 0.575; bottom-peaked 0.25.\n95\t\n96\t**Table 26 — Peaking factors (Pn / Plinear) by zone:**\n97\t| NSTF Zone | Linear | Bottom Peak | Mid-Plane |\n98\t|---|---|---|---|\n99\t|1|1.0|1.225|0.498|\n100\t|2|1.0|1.325|0.831|\n101\t|3|1.0|1.425|1.010|\n102\t|4|1.0|1.375|1.140|\n103\t|5|1.0|1.275|1.248|\n104\t|6|1.0|1.150|1.313|\n105\t|7|1.0|0.900|1.294|\n106\t|8|1.0|0.650|1.157|\n107\t|9|1.0|0.450|0.904|\n108\t|10|1.0|0.225|0.605|\n109\t\n110\t### 4.2 Azimuthal power skew (§6.4.3)\n111\tNSTF has only two azimuthal zones. To mimic the MHTGR cavity azimuthal skew, the prescribed control\n112\tinput was a **125% vs 75% power split** between the two azimuthal heater zones. (Applied in Run026,\n113\tlinear/azimuthal profile, dual vertical, natural circulation.)\n114\t\n115\t---\n116\t\n117\t## 5. Off-normal / prototypic test-case definitions (controlled inputs)\n118\t\n119\t### 5.1 Adjacent chimney roles + short-circuit — Run017 (§7.3.3)\n120\t- Config: **adjacent** chimney roles — south chimney connected to the inlet downcomer via a 24″\n121\t  flexible duct as sole air intake; north chimney is the exhaust. Natural circulation.\n122\t- Heater: one steady-state period at **78 kWe** (~6 h), linear profile.\n123\t- Short-circuit sequence: cross-connect damper LF-CX opened to three break levels **33.3%, 50%,\n124\t  100%** of open flow area; each held 30 min, with 60 min between to re-establish steady state.\n125\t\n126\t### 5.2 Blocked riser channels — Run015 (§7.4.1)\n127\t- Config: start at normal load (700 kWt full → **26.16 kWt** NSTF), linear, single vertical chimney,\n128\t  natural circulation.\n129\t- Blockage stages: **16.6%, 33.3%, 50%** blockage = physically closing **2, 4, 6** riser channels\n130\t  via inlet mechanical flaps. Specific closures: risers (2,3), then +(10,12), then +(5,8). Each stage\n131\t  held ≥ 6 h.\n132\t\n133\t### 5.3 Heavy-gas (argon) ingress — Run027 (§7.4.2)\n134\t- Config: establish steady normal air operation (700 kWt full → 26.16 kWt NSTF), single vertical\n135\t  chimney, natural circulation; then transition inlet gas from air to argon (single-variable change).\n136\t- Argon acceptance target: **≥ 1,000 cu-ft** available gas volume at **< 1% O₂ (≥ 95% argon)**.\n137\t  (Exec. summary: ≈ 1,200 cu-ft of heavy gas was introduced — ~twice the internal flow-path volume.)\n138\t- Gas enclosure (above the downcomer inlet): **7 × 10 × 15 ft**, uni-strut frame wrapped in two\n139\t  layers of 6-mil (0.006″) LDPE film. A central 24″-dia air duct (normal draw) plus four 12″-dia\n140\t  bypass valves at the top corners (argon ingress mode); identical inlet flow area in both modes.\n141\t- (Argon/air physical properties for this scenario are in 02_materials.md, Tables 46–47.)\n142\t\n143\t### 5.4 I-NERI scaling-philosophy test — Run023 (§7.3.4)\n144\t- Collaboration with KAERI and UW comparing scaling philosophies. On the NSTF the case was run in a\n145\t  **forced-flow** configuration (exhaust out the horizontal lofts, forced fan blowers; valves after\n146\t  the outlet plenum and before the lofts dampened to add resistance), linear profile.\n147\t- Two prescribed cases: **Case I** preserves Richardson number (RiR = 1.0); **Case II** preserves\n148\t  heat flux (q″R = 1.0). Target heated ΔT = 98 °C for both. (Per-case scaled target flow/power values\n149\t  appear in the report's Table 42; treat as design targets.)\n150\t\n151\t---\n152\t\n153\t## 6. Ambient / meteorological boundary conditions (§1.5, §7.3.2)\n154\tAmbient conditions are external boundary inputs (the report shows they strongly influence natural\n155\tcirculation). The tested ambient envelope:\n156\t- **Outdoor temperature range across the program: −18.1 °C to +32.1 °C** (§1.5).\n157\t- Baseline (Run011) was run on a \"fair, typical Midwestern winter day\" (§7.1) — i.e., near-freezing\n158\t  ambient, low wind.\n159\t- Accident-scenario executions bracketed the seasonal range (§7.3.2): **Run014 (winter)** ambient\n160\t  averaging ~10 °C (span ≈ 2.9–22.5 °C); **Run018 (summer)** ambient averaging ~25 °C\n161\t  (span ≈ 19.1–32.1 °C).\n162\t- A modeler should treat outdoor air temperature, barometric pressure, humidity, and wind\n163\t  (speed/direction) as prescribed boundary conditions within the envelope above; instrument ranges\n164\t  for these are in 03_instrumentation.md.\n165\t\n166\tZero-flow / initial condition: the facility is brought to a sealed zero-flow state (all five chimney\n167\tvalves closed, inlet plenum sealed) before power ramp; the working gas and structure start near\n168\tambient/indoor temperature (§7.1).\n169\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d866f6b4-d360-4fea-b150-307ad8af7258","uuid":"1de3cd94-7887-41ce-8801-889a5a59a1f9","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:47:31.688Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/root/bench/curated_v2/inputs/04_conditions.md","content":"# 04 — Heater System & Test-Case Definitions (Controlled Inputs)\n\nControlled/boundary inputs from ANL-ART-47: heater power system (§4.3), baseline test definition\n(§7.1), the accident decay-heat scenario (§6.4.1), power-shaping profiles (§6.4.2–§6.4.3), off-normal\ntest-case definitions (§7.3–§7.4), and the ambient envelope (§1.5). Only *prescribed/controlled*\nquantities are given; no measured system responses (flows, gas/wall/plate temperatures, removed\npower, ΔP, efficiency, fluxes) are included.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Heater power system & control (§3.3.5, §4.3)\n- Source: **200 ceramic radiant heaters** (6″×12″×0.5″), 1,100 W each, **max 220 kWe**. Powered by\n  480 & 240 VAC; 120 VAC per element.\n- **40 control zones** = 20 \"main\" (8 heaters each) + 20 \"guard\" (2 heaters each). Nominal split:\n  **80% of power from main zones, 20% from guard zones** (guards trim temperature uniformity).\n- Spatial control grid: overall height split into **ten 67-cm axial segments**; at each axial\n  elevation there are **4 azimuthal zones** (2 central + 2 guard) → 40 zones total.\n- Operating modes: (i) constant heat flux (**max 21.6 kW/m²**), (ii) constant temperature\n  (**max 677 °C**), or (iii) an arbitrary combination.\n- Controllers: 40× **Eurotherm EPower** (600 VAC, 50 A), ±1% of full-scale power regulation;\n  arranged in 5 banks × 4 substations; each zone hard-wired to a Mini8 controller with a safety\n  trip set-point. Power-control mode moved from Phase-Angle to **Burst Firing** in later testing.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Baseline test case — the primary controlled reference (§3.5, §7.1)\n\nThe baseline simulates the GA-MHTGR depressurized-conduction-cooldown (DCC) **peak** decay-heat load\nof 1.5 MWt full scale → **56 kWt** in the NSTF. Config (`baseline` operating state):\n\n1. **Heated–riser spacing:** 70.66 cm (27.82″).\n2. **Outlet-plenum floor height:** 40.64 cm.\n3. **Heater profile & power:** variable-burst, **linear across the 40 zones**; setpoints **56 kWe**\n   and **82 kWe** (a 1st ramp to 56 kWe, then a 2nd ramp so that, after heat losses, ≈ 56 kWt reaches\n   the heated section).\n4. **Chimney:** open vertical stacks; cross-connect (XC) and fan lofts closed.\n5. **Flow mode:** natural circulation; **dual vertical chimney** configuration.\n\nRun011 (the reference baseline run) prescribed two steady-state hold periods: **56 kWe** held ~6 h,\nthen **82 kWe** held ~16 h. (Table 10 lists the nominal baseline heater power as 78 kWe; the\nexecutive summary and §7.1 describe the baseline near ~82 kWe.)\n\nBaseline \"as-set\" configuration values (from §3.5, Table 10): riser–heater spacing 0.71 m; riser flow\narea 0.155 m²; outlet-plenum floor spacing 0.41 m; outlet-plenum depth 1.88 m; chimney discharge\nheight 19.6 m; chimney flow area 0.58 m²; flow operation natural.\n\n---\n\n## 3. GA-MHTGR accident decay-heat scenario (§6.4.1, §7.3.1)\n\nScenario: begin at **normal** steady operation (700 kWt full → **26.16 kWt** NSTF), then follow a\nprescribed decay-heat time history up to the DCC-with-small-primary-leak **peak** (1.5 MWt full →\n**56.07 kWt** NSTF). Linear profile, natural circulation, dual vertical chimney.\n\n### Table 25 — Scaling ratios & resulting values (§6.4.1)\n| Parameter | Scaling ratio | Full scale | ANL 1/2 scale |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Power (normal) | Q̇R = √lR | 700 kWt | 26.16 kWt |\n| Power (DCC accident) | Q̇R = √lR | 1,500 kWt | 56.07 kWt |\n| Time | TR* = √lR | 120 hr | 84.85 hr |\n\n### Prescribed electrical-power decay curve (§6.4.1)\nThe GA \"RCCS Removal\" decay curve was digitized, normalized to a peak of 1.5 MWt, and fit to a\npolynomial. The programmed NSTF electric power is:\n\n`P_watt,electric = [ C00 + C01·t + C02·t² + … + C09·t⁹ ] × Pscale`, with **t in minutes**,\nand **Pscale = 90** (estimated to yield ≈ 56 kWt peak).\n\nFitted coefficients:\n```\nC00 =  466.531039994\nC01 =  0.078631095079\nC02 =  0.000170562320568\nC03 = -1.28449427566e-007\nC04 =  5.09424812301e-011\nC05 = -1.27606140005e-014\nC06 =  2.04789514471e-018\nC07 = -2.08318254453e-022\nC08 =  1.29530038954e-026\nC09 = -4.48601180685e-031\n```\nCorrelation coefficient 0.999958043125; standard error about the line 1.46350115015.\n(Report text describes a 10th-order fit; coefficients through C09 are those tabulated.)\n\nRun014/Run018 executed this scenario: initiate at normal steady load, then follow the scaled curve to\nthe peak. (Run014 and Run018 are the winter and summer executions — see ambient conditions below.)\n\n---\n\n## 4. Power-shaping profiles (§6.4.2–§6.4.3)\n\n### 4.1 Cosine axial power profile (§6.4.2, Table 26)\nAxial power skews were fit to the 40 zones with the integral power preserved. Peak positions\n(normalized 0–1 axial): true cosine 0.5; MHTGR mid-plane 0.575; bottom-peaked 0.25.\n\n**Table 26 — Peaking factors (Pn / Plinear) by zone:**\n| NSTF Zone | Linear | Bottom Peak | Mid-Plane |\n|---|---|---|---|\n|1|1.0|1.225|0.498|\n|2|1.0|1.325|0.831|\n|3|1.0|1.425|1.010|\n|4|1.0|1.375|1.140|\n|5|1.0|1.275|1.248|\n|6|1.0|1.150|1.313|\n|7|1.0|0.900|1.294|\n|8|1.0|0.650|1.157|\n|9|1.0|0.450|0.904|\n|10|1.0|0.225|0.605|\n\n### 4.2 Azimuthal power skew (§6.4.3)\nNSTF has only two azimuthal zones. To mimic the MHTGR cavity azimuthal skew, the prescribed control\ninput was a **125% vs 75% power split** between the two azimuthal heater zones. (Applied in Run026,\nlinear/azimuthal profile, dual vertical, natural circulation.)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Off-normal / prototypic test-case definitions (controlled inputs)\n\n### 5.1 Adjacent chimney roles + short-circuit — Run017 (§7.3.3)\n- Config: **adjacent** chimney roles — south chimney connected to the inlet downcomer via a 24″\n  flexible duct as sole air intake; north chimney is the exhaust. Natural circulation.\n- Heater: one steady-state period at **78 kWe** (~6 h), linear profile.\n- Short-circuit sequence: cross-connect damper LF-CX opened to three break levels **33.3%, 50%,\n  100%** of open flow area; each held 30 min, with 60 min between to re-establish steady state.\n\n### 5.2 Blocked riser channels — Run015 (§7.4.1)\n- Config: start at normal load (700 kWt full → **26.16 kWt** NSTF), linear, single vertical chimney,\n  natural circulation.\n- Blockage stages: **16.6%, 33.3%, 50%** blockage = physically closing **2, 4, 6** riser channels\n  via inlet mechanical flaps. Specific closures: risers (2,3), then +(10,12), then +(5,8). Each stage\n  held ≥ 6 h.\n\n### 5.3 Heavy-gas (argon) ingress — Run027 (§7.4.2)\n- Config: establish steady normal air operation (700 kWt full → 26.16 kWt NSTF), single vertical\n  chimney, natural circulation; then transition inlet gas from air to argon (single-variable change).\n- Argon acceptance target: **≥ 1,000 cu-ft** available gas volume at **< 1% O₂ (≥ 95% argon)**.\n  (Exec. summary: ≈ 1,200 cu-ft of heavy gas was introduced — ~twice the internal flow-path volume.)\n- Gas enclosure (above the downcomer inlet): **7 × 10 × 15 ft**, uni-strut frame wrapped in two\n  layers of 6-mil (0.006″) LDPE film. A central 24″-dia air duct (normal draw) plus four 12″-dia\n  bypass valves at the top corners (argon ingress mode); identical inlet flow area in both modes.\n- (Argon/air physical properties for this scenario are in 02_materials.md, Tables 46–47.)\n\n### 5.4 I-NERI scaling-philosophy test — Run023 (§7.3.4)\n- Collaboration with KAERI and UW comparing scaling philosophies. On the NSTF the case was run in a\n  **forced-flow** configuration (exhaust out the horizontal lofts, forced fan blowers; valves after\n  the outlet plenum and before the lofts dampened to add resistance), linear profile.\n- Two prescribed cases: **Case I** preserves Richardson number (RiR = 1.0); **Case II** preserves\n  heat flux (q″R = 1.0). Target heated ΔT = 98 °C for both. (Per-case scaled target flow/power values\n  appear in the report's Table 42; treat as design targets.)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Ambient / meteorological boundary conditions (§1.5, §7.3.2)\nAmbient conditions are external boundary inputs (the report shows they strongly influence natural\ncirculation). The tested ambient envelope:\n- **Outdoor temperature range across the program: −18.1 °C to +32.1 °C** (§1.5).\n- Baseline (Run011) was run on a \"fair, typical Midwestern winter day\" (§7.1) — i.e., near-freezing\n  ambient, low wind.\n- Accident-scenario executions bracketed the seasonal range (§7.3.2): **Run014 (winter)** ambient\n  averaging ~10 °C (span ≈ 2.9–22.5 °C); **Run018 (summer)** ambient averaging ~25 °C\n  (span ≈ 19.1–32.1 °C).\n- A modeler should treat outdoor air temperature, barometric pressure, humidity, and wind\n  (speed/direction) as prescribed boundary conditions within the envelope above; instrument ranges\n  for these are in 03_instrumentation.md.\n\nZero-flow / initial condition: the facility is brought to a sealed zero-flow state (all five chimney\nvalves closed, inlet plenum sealed) before power ramp; the working gas and structure start near\nambient/indoor temperature (§7.1).\n","numLines":169,"startLine":1,"totalLines":169}}}
